'''Robert Rolla Woolsey''' (August 14, 1888 &ndash; October 31, 1938) was an [[United States|American]] stage and screen [[comedian]] and half of the 1930s comedy team [[Wheeler & Woolsey]].
==Early life == He was born in [[Oakland, California]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=XFnfnKg6BcAC&pg=PA1229&lpg=PA1229&dq Cullen, Frank; Hackman, Florence; McNeilly, Donald (2007). ''Vaudeville, Old & New''. Routledge]. {{ISBN|0-415-93853-8}} p. 1229.</ref> Woolsey always had a slight build, and as a young adult he tried to capitalize on it by becoming a jockey. After he fell from a horse and sustained an injury, he quit racing and turned instead to the stage. In 1925 he was featured as "Mortimer Pottle" in [[W. C. Fields]]'s Broadway hit ''[[Poppy (1923 musical)|Poppy]]''.
==Wheeler and Woolsey == Woolsey was teamed with comedy star [[Bert Wheeler]] in 1928, for the Broadway musical ''[[Rio Rita (musical)|Rio Rita]]''. [[RKO Radio Pictures]] filmed the play in 1929, launching Wheeler and Woolsey as movie personalities. Of the twenty-two films Woolsey would make, twenty-one of them would be with his comedy partner, Wheeler.
Woolsey became terminally ill in 1937 and struggled to finish his last picture, ''High Flyers''. He was then confined to bed for almost a full year, before dying of kidney failure in 1938.<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Robert Woolsey, Film Comedian, 49. Partner of Bert Wheeler in Many Pictures and on the Stage Dies in California. In First 'Rio Rita' Cast. That New York Success Led to Movie Contract. Big Cigar Was His Principal Prop. Played in Stock on Coast. Won Honors With Ziegfeld |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9C07EEDA163BEE3ABC4953DFB7678383629EDE |quote=Robert Woolsey, motion picture comedian, died today at his home here after a long illness at the age of 49. ... |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=November 1, 1938 |accessdate=2015-01-04 }}</ref> Robert Woolsey was interred in the [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park Cemetery]] in [[Glendale, California]].
